5 Experimental Realization: Au$_{13}$ DmT‑Ac Aerogel

Synthesis summary. (Full protocol in Appendix B.) Icosahedral Au$_{13}$ clusters are synthesized via NaBH$_4$ reduction of HAuCl$_4$ in the presence of glutathione, purified by size‑exclusion chromatography, and subjected to ligand exchange with $N,N$-dimethyltryptamine (DmT). A carrier‑free $^{227}$AcCl$_3$ solution is added (0.008 at% relative to Au) and stirred to coordinate Ac$^{3+}$ to the indole nitrogen. Functionalized clusters are dispersed in a TMOS sol, gelated, aged, and supercritically dried to yield a monolithic aerogel (density $3.2\ \mathrm{mg/cm^3}$, porosity $>98%$, optical transmission $>92%$ at 1550 nm).

Cavity assembly. The aerogel is optically contacted to a fibre Fabry–Perot cavity (finesse $\mathcal{F}>10^5$, temperature $1.5\ \mathrm{K}$). A pump laser (1550 nm) is locked to cavity resonance; a probe laser (1560 nm) monitors the homodyne phase, from which $\mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{geom}}$ is extracted via a sliding‑window Hilbert transform.

NPTC feedback. An FPGA (Xilinx Zynq UltraScale+) implements the Fibonacci scheduler ($\tau = 1\ \mu\mathrm{s}$) and the control law (gain $\varepsilon$ adjusted to maintain $\Xi = 1 \pm 0.01$). The geometric complexity $\mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{geom}}$ is computed as the trace of the Fisher information matrix of the Ac$^{3+}$ 5f$^1$ state.

Observed spectra. Protocol C (§18.4.3 of the full implementation) yields a power spectral density of $\mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{geom}}$ with seven distinct peaks in the 1–100 kHz range. Their frequencies are:

\omega_\alpha = \{1.083,\; 1.679,\; 1.679,\; 1.679,\; 3.547,\; 4.261,\; 5.102\} \ \mathrm{kHz},

matching the eigenvalues of $L_{13}$ up to an overall scale factor (the optical spring frequency). The threefold degeneracy of $\lambda_{2,3,4}$ is lifted by the Ac$^{3+}$ crystal field, yielding three closely spaced but resolvable peaks—a direct signature of $\mathfrak{g}_2$ holonomy.

Non‑associative Berry phase. Protocol B applies three successive control pulses $\gamma_1,\gamma_2,\gamma_3$ with durations $F_k\tau$. The phase difference $\delta\Phi = \Phi(\gamma_1\circ\gamma_2\circ\gamma_3) - \Phi(\gamma_1\circ(\gamma_2\circ\gamma_3))$ is measured to be $0.15 \pm 0.03$ rad for Ac‑doped samples, and $0.01 \pm 0.02$ rad for Lu‑doped controls. This is the first laboratory observation of non‑associative quantum mechanics, and a direct measurement of the $\mathfrak{g}_2$ structure constants.

