6 p‑Laplacian Kernels and Ergotropy Optimization

Define the $p$-Laplacian kernel on the discrete Laplacian $L_N$:

K_\varepsilon^{(p)} = -L_N^{-1} + \varepsilon L_N^{-p},\qquad p>1.

Its eigenvalues are $\mu_k^{(p)} = \varepsilon \lambda_k^{-p} - \lambda_k^{-1}$. Positivity of $K_\varepsilon^{(p)}$ (i.e., $\mu_k \ge 0$ for all $k$) requires $\varepsilon \ge \lambda_1^{p-1}$. The critical threshold

\varepsilon_{\mathrm{crit}} = \lambda_1(L_N)^{\,p-1}

is the minimum feedback gain that prevents violation of the second law (§2, entropy balance). In the continuum limit, $\lambda_1(L_N) \to 2$, so $\varepsilon_{\mathrm{crit}} \to 2^{p-1}$.

The ergotropy perturbation $\Delta W(\delta r) = \delta , \delta r^\top K_\varepsilon^{(p)} \delta r$ is the work that would be extracted if the controller attempted to “cool” the system. The constraint $\Delta W \ge 0$ is a convex quadratic program in the modal coefficients $c_k$. Its solution is a spectral projection onto the non‑negative eigenspace—implemented in real time by the FPGA as a single multiply‑accumulate operation per Fibonacci interval.

---

7 Octonionic Holonomy and the Fano Plane

The Ac$^{3+}$ 5f$^1$ electron in the chiral ligand field of DmT exhibits a $\mathfrak{g}_2$-valued Berry connection when the control parameters $(\Delta,\theta)$ are cycled. The seven imaginary octonions $e_1,\ldots,e_7$ correspond to the seven infinitesimal generators of $\mathfrak{g}_2$ that rotate the Fano‑plane incidence structure.

The Fano plane is the unique projective plane of order 2, with seven points and seven lines (each line containing three points). Its adjacency matrix has eigenvalues $0,2,2,2,4,4,4$. Under the Ac$^{3+}$ crystal field, this degeneracy is lifted, producing the seven distinct $\omega_\alpha$ measured in Protocol C. The non‑associative Berry phase $\Phi_{\mathrm{na}}$ is proportional to the triple product of path‑ordered exponentials:

U(\gamma_1)U(\gamma_2)U(\gamma_3) - U(\gamma_1)U(\gamma_2\gamma_3) \neq 0,

with the discrepancy given by the $\mathfrak{g}_2$ structure constants. Our measured $\delta\Phi$ (Section 5) quantitatively matches the prediction from the holonomy cocycle $H$.

