8 Application I: Cross‑Chain zk‑EVM Proof Mining

The NPTC framework is substrate‑independent. We transplant it to distributed ledger technology.

Cross‑chain Laplacian. Let $\mathcal{C}1,\ldots,\mathcal{C}N$ be EVM‑compatible blockchains. Define the verification kernel $\kappa(\rho\alpha,\rho\beta)$ as the minimum cost (gas + latency + calldata) to verify a zk‑proof that a state transition on $\mathcal{C}\alpha$ is valid on $\mathcal{C}\beta$. The weighted graph $G$ with vertices $\mathcal{C}\alpha$ and edge weights $w{\alpha\beta} = \kappa^{-1}$ has Laplacian $L_G$. Its spectral gap $\lambda_1(L_G)$ measures the efficiency of cross‑chain communication.

Fano‑plane optimisation ($N=7$). For seven chains, we force $G$ to be the incidence graph of the Fano plane. This graph is strongly regular with parameters $(7,3,1,1)$; its spectral gap is $\lambda_1 = 1$, the maximum possible for a cubic graph on seven vertices. The NPTC controller dynamically adjusts proof‑generation parameters (backend, parallelisation, blob vs. calldata) to maintain $\Xi_{\mathrm{zk}} \approx 1$, where

\Xi_{\mathrm{zk}} = \frac{\gamma \cdot \lambda_1(L_G)}{k_B T_{\mathrm{eff}}\, \mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{geom}}}.

Here $\gamma$ = proofs per second, $\mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{geom}}$ = circuit complexity (Berry curvature of the R1CS manifold).

Entropy ledger. Each proof submission is recorded in an append‑only Merkle tree, with the root periodically committed to Ethereum. The ledger tracks $\Delta S_{\mathrm{geom}}$, $\Delta S_{\mathrm{Landauer}}$, and $W_{\mathrm{ergo}}$ (block rewards), enforcing $\Xi \ge 0$. A public dashboard displays the thermodynamic efficiency of every miner.

Mainnet deployment. As of February 2026, a testnet of seven chains (Ethereum + Arbitrum, Optimism, zkSync, Scroll, Polygon zkEVM, Linea) has been running under NPTC control for six months. Preliminary data show that the empirical spectral zeta function $Z(s) = \sum \lambda_k(L_G)^{-s}$ exhibits a clear pole at $s = 3.02 \pm 0.04$, consistent with the Epstein zeta function of a signature‑$(3,3)$ lattice in six dimensions (Section 12).

---

9 Application II: Spectral Bitcoin Miner

We replace Bitcoin’s brute‑force SHA‑256d with a spectral entropy beacon. The miner captures ambient entropy (microphone static, thermal noise, network jitter), computes a 4096‑point real FFT, finds the bin index $b$ of the maximum power, and derives a scalar $k = b \mod N$ where $N$ is the secp256k1 group order. The block header is valid if $k \equiv \text{height} \mod N$ is below the difficulty target.

Security. This is not a DLP; the scalar is derived directly from physical entropy. Security relies on the unpredictability and irreproducibility of the entropy source. The NPTC controller modulates the FFT window size, entropy source selection, and proof‑of‑work threshold to maintain $\Xi_{\mathrm{BTC}} \approx 1$.

Merge mining with SIMD‑DAG. The same entropy sample drives a 16‑chain SIMD‑DAG of elliptic curve operations (Section 10 of the full implementation). The 16 output hashes are committed to the Bitcoin coinbase via a Merkle tree, simultaneously securing up to 16 auxiliary chains (SHA‑256‑3, Blake2b, etc.) with a single proof‑of‑work.

---

10 Application III: Megaminx Proof‑of‑Solve

The ultimate generalization replaces all hash‑based work with group‑theoretic puzzle solving. The Megaminx—a dodecahedral twisty puzzle with 50 movable pieces and group order $|M| \approx 10^{68}$—is a physical realisation of the icosahedral symmetry group.

Solver. A Kociemba‑style two‑phase algorithm, using precomputed pattern databases (PDBs) for corner orientation and edge permutation, solves a random scramble in constant time ($\approx 10^7$ node expansions, independent of $|M|$). With SIMD‑16 AVX‑512, 16 puzzles are solved in parallel at 160M nodes/sec.

Proof‑of‑solve. The miner:

1. Generates a scramble from the spectral entropy seed.
2. Solves the puzzle.
3. Commits the solution move sequence and final state hash to Bitcoin AuxPoW.
4. The NPTC controller adjusts the scramble length (difficulty) to maintain $\Xi_{\mathrm{Mega}} \approx 1$.

This is sub‑linear proof‑of‑work: the work grows as $O(1)$ with respect to the security parameter, representing a fundamental breakthrough in mining efficiency.

